Before the Ryazan you see now, there was Old Ryazan, or Старая Рязань. A capital of the [Principality of Ryazan](/Principality_of_Ryazan), it stood proud until the [Mongol invasion](/Mongol_invasion_of_Kievan_Rus%27) of 1237. That was a rough time. The city was besieged, razed, and essentially erased. The capital shifted to Pereyaslavl-Ryazansky, a place that eventually, by decree of [Catherine the Great](/Catherine_the_Great) in 1778, became Ryazan. Funny how history works, isn't it? A name survives, even if the original city doesn't.

It's a place with some cultural heft, too. The [Ryazan Kremlin](/Ryazan_Kremlin), a relic of days gone by. The [Pozhalostin Museum](/Pozhalostin_Museum), one of Russia’s older art collections. And then there’s the Memorial Museum-Estate of Academician [I.P. Pavlov](/Ivan_Pavlov) – yes, *that* Pavlov, the dog guy. And for the aviation enthusiasts, the [Ryazan Museum of Long-Range Aviation](/Ryazan_Museum_of_Long-Range_Aviation).

In 2022, Ryazan managed to snag a spot in the top three for urban digitalization, at least for cities of its size. Apparently, they’re not entirely stuck in the past.

## History

### Principality of Ryazan

• See also: [Principality of Ryazan](/Principality_of_Ryazan)

![Old map of Ryazan (1909)](/Old_map_of_Ryazan_(1909))

The first mention of this place, then called Pereslavl, surfaces in 1095. It eventually became the heart of the independent [Principality of Ryazan](/Principality_of_Ryazan), established around 1129. The first in line? Supposedly [Yaroslav Sviatoslavich](/Yaroslav_Sviatoslavich), a prince who held sway over Ryazan and Murom, two significant cities in [Kievan Rus'](/Kievan_Rus%27). It’s a lineage that stretches back, even if the details are a bit hazy.

### Invasion by Mongols

• Further information: [Mongol invasion of Europe](/Mongol_invasion_of_Europe)

By the 12th century, Ryazan was caught in the crossfire. Situated between the forests and the [steppe](/Steppe), it was a frequent target for raids from both the southern and northern factions of European Russia. The Cumans were a persistent nuisance from the south, while Vladimir-Suzdal to the north saw fit to burn the capital multiple times by the century's end.

Then came the 13th century. Ryazan became the unfortunate **first Russian city** to face the full force of the [Mongol invasion](/Mongol_invasion_of_Kievan_Rus%27), led by [Batu Khan](/Batu_Khan). On December 21, 1237, after a brief but brutal siege, the city was [completely destroyed](/The_Tale_of_the_Destruction_of_Ryazan). It never truly recovered. The seat of power was forced to relocate about 55 kilometers to Pereslavl-Ryazansky, which then adopted the name of its fallen predecessor. The original site is now known as Staraya Ryazan (Old Ryazan), not far from [Spassk-Ryazansky](/Spassk-Ryazansky). For centuries, even into the 18th, maps would show both Ryazan and Pereslavl-Ryazan, a testament to the fractured memory of what was lost.

### Golden Horde

![Old Ryazan remnants: Cathedral of St. Boris and Gleb](/Cathedral_of_St._Boris_and_Gleb)
![Ryazan Kremlin](/Ryazan_Kremlin)

In 1380, during the [Battle of Kulikovo](/Battle_of_Kulikovo), Ryazan’s Grand Prince Oleg found himself allied with [Mamai](/Mamai) of the [Golden Horde](/Golden_Horde) and the Grand Duke of [Lithuania](/Grand_Duchy_of_Lithuania). Their target? The forces of [Dmitry Donskoy](/Dmitry_Donskoy), Grand Prince of [Vladimir](/Vladimir,_Russia). A complex web of alliances and rivalries, as always.

By the late 13th century, the Ryazan princes had already moved their capital to Pereyaslavl. It wasn't until the 16th century that it started being called Ryazan, and the official renaming to Ryazan happened in 1778.

The principality's independent run ended in 1521 when it was absorbed into the [Grand Duchy of Moscow](/Grand_Duchy_of_Moscow). The last duke, [Ivan V of Ryazan](/Ivan_V_of_Ryazan), was suspected of plotting with the [Crimean Khanate](/Crimean_Khanate) to check Moscow's growing power. He fled to Lithuania and died sometime before 1534.

Ryazan, being on the southern frontier, continued to be a target for the [Crimean Tatars](/Crimean_Tatars) and their allies. Always on the edge, always vulnerable.

