### Time of Troubles

• Main article: [Time of Troubles](/Time_of_Troubles)
• See also: [Polish–Muscovite War (1605–1618)](/Polish%E2%80%93Muscovite_War_(1605%E2%80%931618))

In June 1605, Ryazan welcomed [Patriarch Ignatius](/Ignatius_of_Moscow), a [clergyman](/Clergyman) of [Greek Cypriot](/Greek_Cypriot) origin. Sent by the [Russian Orthodox Church](/Russian_Orthodox_Church) to serve as [Archbishop](/Archbishop) of Ryazan, he gained notoriety for being the first church official to acknowledge the Polish-backed impostor, False Dmitry, as the legitimate Tsar of the [Tsardom of Russia](/Tsardom_of_Russia) after meeting his troops in [Tula](/Tula,_Russia).

Around this tumultuous period, Ryazan became a haven for various noble families, most notably the Lyapunovs. Brothers [Prokopy Lyapunov](/Prokopy_Petrovich_Lyapunov) and [Zakhary Lyapunov](/Zakhary_Lyapunov) would play significant roles in the unfolding drama of the [Time of Troubles](/Time_of_Troubles).

### Soviet Union

• See also: [Ryazan miracle](/Ryazan_miracle)

During [World War II](/World_War_II), Ryazan endured repeated bombings by the German [Luftwaffe](/Luftwaffe). Post-war, the city saw rapid development, transforming into a significant industrial, scientific, and military hub in European Russia. [20] [22] On October 19, 1960, the local [petroleum refinery](/Oil_refinery) churned out its first batch of gasoline. [23]

Ryazan was also the sole producer of potato-harvesting equipment in the USSR. Factories like Ryazselmash ('Ryazan Countryside Machines'), an accounting machines plant, and a heavy forging equipment plant were established. [22] This industrial surge led to a shift in Ryazan Oblast's workforce, with many moving from agriculture to industry. [22]

The city became a crucial military center, serving as the primary training ground for the [Soviet Airborne Forces](/Soviet_Airborne_Forces). The skies above Ryazan were protected by [man-portable air-defense systems](/Man-portable_air-defense_system). Beyond the Airborne School (then named after [Kliment Voroshilov](/Kliment_Voroshilov)), [20] Ryazan housed an Automobile School, an Institute of Communications, a regiment of [railway troops](/Russian_Railway_Troops), a strategic bomber airbase, and a training center in Diaghilev.

Nadezhda Nikolaevna Chumakova's tenure as Chair of the Council of People's Deputies and later mayor saw significant growth. The city's population swelled from 72,000 to 520,000 under her leadership. She oversaw the construction of social and cultural facilities, numerous housing developments, and extensive public transport networks. Landscaping became a priority, with a "green" ring of forests and parks encircling the city. Ryazan consistently received accolades for its urban planning and greenery, even winning the [Red Banner](/Red_Banner) of the USSR multiple times.

### Post-Soviet period

• See also: [Collapse of the Soviet Union](/Collapse_of_the_Soviet_Union) and [1998 Russian financial crisis](/1998_Russian_financial_crisis)

•

This section feels like a placeholder. It needs updating. The 90s were a mess for many places, and Ryazan was no exception. The collapse of the Soviet Union meant a significant chunk of the city's GDP, over half, was being exported to its former [satellite states](/Satellite_state). The [1998 Russian financial crisis](/1998_Russian_financial_crisis) hit hard, leading to numerous bankruptcies. Then came the attempted [apartment bombings](/Russian_apartment_bombings) in September 1999, an event known as the Ryazan Incident. By 2001, Ryazan was still heavily influenced by the neighboring [Moscow Oblast](/Moscow_Oblast).

